# Runtime Theme Resource with Type Variations and Light/Dark Switching

## Background
Godot 4's GUI skinning system uses the `Theme` resource to drive how every `Control` node is rendered. A theme stores typed items (colors, fonts, font sizes, constants, icons, styleboxes), organized by *theme types* (e.g. `Button`, `Label`, `Panel`). On top of the built-in types, themes can declare **type variations**: named theme types that inherit from a base built-in type and override a subset of items. A `Control` opts into a variation by setting `theme_type_variation` (or by calling `set_theme_type_variation()`), and any unmatched item falls back to the base type.

In this task you will build a small Godot 4 project that constructs a `Theme` resource entirely at runtime (not via the inspector and not loaded from a `.tres`), wires it to a root `Control`, exposes a public API to swap between a "light" and a "dark" variant at runtime, and provides two custom button type variations: `PrimaryButton` and `DangerButton`.

Godot 4 (>= 4.3) is installed as the headless binary `godot` in `PATH`.

## Requirements
- The project root must be `/home/user/theme_lab` and contain a valid `project.godot` with the main scene set to `res://scenes/main.tscn`.
- The main scene `res://scenes/main.tscn` must have the following node hierarchy (names matter exactly):
  - `Root` (type `Control`) with the project's main script attached.
    - `MainPanel` (type `Panel`).
      - `TitleLabel` (type `Label`).
      - `DefaultButton` (type `Button`, no `theme_type_variation`).
      - `PrimaryButton` (type `Button`, `theme_type_variation = "PrimaryButton"`).
      - `DangerButton` (type `Button`, `theme_type_variation = "DangerButton"`).
- The main script must expose a public API on the `Root` node:
  - `apply_theme(mode: String) -> void` builds a brand-new `Theme` resource **at runtime via code** for the requested mode (`"light"` or `"dark"`) and assigns it to `Root.theme`. The theme MUST be constructed by GDScript on every call (not preloaded from a `.tres` resource file).
  - `get_current_mode() -> String` returns the last mode passed to `apply_theme` (`"light"` or `"dark"`). Before any call it must return `"light"`.
  - On `_ready`, the script must call `apply_theme("light")` so the scene starts in light mode.
- The runtime-built theme must register two type variations of base type `Button`:
  - `PrimaryButton` (variation of `Button`)
  - `DangerButton` (variation of `Button`)
  Use `Theme.set_type_variation(variation, base_type)` so that controls with `theme_type_variation = "PrimaryButton"` inherit from `Button` and only override what `PrimaryButton` defines.
- For each Button-like theme type (`Button`, `PrimaryButton`, `DangerButton`), the theme must define three `StyleBoxFlat` styleboxes named `normal`, `hover`, and `pressed`, each with a distinct `bg_color`. The corner radius (all four corners equal) must match the values listed in Acceptance Criteria.
- For the `Panel` type, the theme must define one `StyleBoxFlat` named `panel` with the required `bg_color`.
- For `Button` and `Label`, the theme must define the `font_color` color item.
- Switching modes must be live: calling `apply_theme("dark")` after `apply_theme("light")` (or vice versa) must update every queryable theme item on every relevant control via `Control.get_theme_color(...)` and `Control.get_theme_stylebox(...)`. Do **not** rely on `add_theme_*_override`; the values must come from the assigned `Theme` resource itself.

## Implementation Hints
- Use `Theme.new()`, `StyleBoxFlat.new()`, and the typed setters on `Theme` (`set_color`, `set_stylebox`, `set_type_variation`). See https://docs.godotengine.org/en/stable/tutorials/ui/gui_skinning.html and the `Theme` class reference.
- For a `StyleBoxFlat`, set `bg_color` and the four `corner_radius_*` properties (or call `set_corner_radius_all(radius)`).
- Variation lookup: when a control has `theme_type_variation = "PrimaryButton"`, `get_theme_stylebox("normal", "Button")` and `get_theme_stylebox("normal")` should both surface the `PrimaryButton.normal` stylebox if the theme has registered the variation correctly. Verifier queries will pass the control's expected theme type explicitly.
- Color values use Godot's `Color(hex_string)` constructor; compare them with a small tolerance (e.g. 1/255) when validating because hex strings round-trip through floats.
- Make sure the project loads cleanly headless: `godot --headless --path /home/user/theme_lab --quit` must exit with code 0 and produce no `SCRIPT ERROR` or `Parse Error`.

